title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {F}=\{F_{i}\}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> be an indexed family of groups. For any group <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> and for any family of <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-000T.xml"
addr="gr-000T"
title="Group Morphism">Group Morphism</fr:link>s <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _{i}\colon  G\to  F_{i}]]></fr:tex>, there exists a unique morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon  G\to \prod \mathcal {F}]]></fr:tex> such that for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in  I]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _{i}\circ \varphi =\varphi _{i}]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _{i}(x)=x_{i}]]></fr:tex> is the projection onto the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> factor of the product group <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _{i}\colon \prod \mathcal {F}\to  F_{i}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
